https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legends_of_Mount_Shasta\n> California's https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta has been the subject of an unusually large number of myths and legends. In particular, it is often said to hide a secret city beneath its peaks. In some stories, the city is no longer inhabited, while in others, it is inhabited by a technologically advanced society of human beings or mythical creatures.\n\n> According to local indigenous tribes, namely the Klamath people, https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta is inhabited by the spirit chief Skell, who descended from heaven to the mountain's summit. Skell fought with Spirit of the Below-World, Llao, who resided at Mount Mazama, by throwing hot rocks and lava, probably representing the volcanic eruptions at both mountains. Writer Joaquin Miller recorded various related legends in the 1870s.\n\n> https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta has also been a focus for non-Native American legends, centered on a hidden city (called Telos) of advanced beings from the lost continent of Lemuria. The legend grew from an offhand mention of Lemuria in the 1880s. In 1899, Frederick Spencer Oliver published A Dweller on Two Planets, which claimed that survivors from a sunken continent called Lemuria were living in or on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta. Oliver's Lemurians lived in a complex of tunnels beneath the mountain and occasionally were seen walking the surface dressed in white robes. In 1931, Harvey Spencer Lewis, using the pseudonym Wisar Spenle Cerve, wrote a book (published by the Rosicrucians) about the hidden Lemurians of https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta that a bibliography on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta described as \"responsible for the legend's widespread popularity.\" This belief has been incorporated into numerous occult religions, including \"I AM\" Activity, The Summit Lighthouse, Church Universal and Triumphant, and Kryon.\n\n> According to Guy Ballard, while hiking on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta, he encountered a man who introduced himself as Count of St. Germain, who is said to have started Ballard on the path to discovering the teachings that would become the \"I AM\" Activity religious movement.\n\n> According to a legend, J. C. Brown was a British prospector who discovered a lost underground city beneath https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta in 1904. Brown had been hired by the Lord Cowdray Mining Company of England to prospect for gold, and discovered a cave which sloped downward for 11 miles. In the cave, he found an underground village filled with gold, shields, and mummies, some being up to 10 feet tall.\n\n> Thirty years later, he told his story to John C. Root, who proceeded to gather an exploration team in Stockton, California. About 80 people joined the team, but on the day the team was to set out, Brown did not show up. -hamblin\n\nhttps://trello.com/c/0WD0443o/2058-%F0%9F%8F%9B%EF%B8%8F-grant-cameron\n\nhttps://trello.com/c/4dFMjJpF/2089-%F0%9F%91%A8%E2%9A%95%EF%B8%8F-dr-steven-greer-%F0%9F%A7%98%E2%99%82%EF%B8%8F","descData":{"emoji":{}},"due":null,"dueReminder":null,"email":"felewin+2r08bk9nr0rwtukl28n+2v0rceia9uijdupg052+22e8bw4gqf@boards.trello.com","idBoard":"5ef6690730145a713865e369","idChecklists":[],"idLabels":[],"idList":"5f473e79b8adab8a7e460ea8","idMemberCreator":null,"idMembers":[],"idMembersVoted":[],"idOrganization":"6125802363cee0583c156347","idShort":1758,"idAttachmentCover":null,"labels":[],"limits":{"attachments":{"perCard":{"status":"ok","disableAt":1000,"warnAt":800}},"checklists":{"perCard":{"status":"ok","disableAt":500,"warnAt":400}},"stickers":{"perCard":{"status":"ok","disableAt":70,"warnAt":56}}},"locationName":null,"manualCoverAttachment":true,"name":"especially https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legends_of_Mount_Shasta\n> California's https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta has been the subject of an unusually large number of myths and legends. In particular, it is often said to hide a secret city beneath its peaks. In some stories, the city is no longer inhabited, while in others, it is inhabited by a technologically advanced society of human beings or mythical creatures.\n\n> According to local indigenous tribes, namely the Klamath people, https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta is inhabited by the spirit chief Skell, who descended from heaven to the mountain's summit. Skell fought with Spirit of the Below-World, Llao, who resided at Mount Mazama, by throwing hot rocks and lava, probably representing the volcanic eruptions at both mountains. Writer Joaquin Miller recorded various related legends in the 1870s.\n\n> https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta has also been a focus for non-Native American legends, centered on a hidden city (called Telos) of advanced beings from the lost continent of Lemuria. The legend grew from an offhand mention of Lemuria in the 1880s. In 1899, Frederick Spencer Oliver published A Dweller on Two Planets, which claimed that survivors from a sunken continent called Lemuria were living in or on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta. Oliver's Lemurians lived in a complex of tunnels beneath the mountain and occasionally were seen walking the surface dressed in white robes. In 1931, Harvey Spencer Lewis, using the pseudonym Wisar Spenle Cerve, wrote a book (published by the Rosicrucians) about the hidden Lemurians of https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta that a bibliography on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta described as \"responsible for the legend's widespread popularity.\" This belief has been incorporated into numerous occult religions, including \"I AM\" Activity, The Summit Lighthouse, Church Universal and Triumphant, and Kryon.\n\n> According to Guy Ballard, while hiking on https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta, he encountered a man who introduced himself as Count of St. Germain, who is said to have started Ballard on the path to discovering the teachings that would become the \"I AM\" Activity religious movement.\n\n> According to a legend, J. C. Brown was a British prospector who discovered a lost underground city beneath https://trello.com/c/Qr1sZx9r/1757-%F0%9F%8F%94%EF%B8%8F-mount-shasta in 1904. Brown had been hired by the Lord Cowdray Mining Company of England to prospect for gold, and discovered a cave which sloped downward for 11 miles. In the cave, he found an underground village filled with gold, shields, and mummies, some being up to 10 feet tall.\n\n> Thirty years later, he told his story to John C. Root, who proceeded to gather an exploration team in Stockton, California. About 80 people joined the team, but on the day the team was to set out, Brown did not show up. Brown was not heard from this hill top, a gathering of people in ancient dress gaze motionless, entranced at the scene taking place before them.  Two figures, the one kneedeep in water, head bowed, hands in attitude of prayer, stoops slightly towards the other who with outstretched arms sprinkles him with water.\n> Something momentous indeed has caught the attention of the surrounding onlookers.  The water and the two figures are bathed in a special kind of light, softly glowing.  High in the sky above hovers a greenish disk at the centre of which is a tiny dove with outstretched wings.  From that disk emanate four narrow rays which seem to travel down to earth penetrating the centre of the place/event below.  The rays seem both to support the disk above and to and to come down as a blessing and completion of the baptism.  But the rays themselves are painted in such a way as not to appear as light beams.  Perhaps some other kind of ‚Äòlight‚Äô is intended.  The peculiar light quality of the scene is enhanced by the glow of the central event; indeed one feels the water to be charged with some spiritual energy.\n\nThis painting is located at the make contact:\nhttps://youtu.be/oNefLifaTVU?t=2603\n\nNotes on information shared by Billy in the documentary:\n'Semjase' is the name by which Billy refers to the main female Pleiadian being he met. She was reportedly quite human in appearance. This is very similar to the description of the Pleiadian-connected Apunians whom Ricardo Gonz√°lez contacts, and serves to corroborate other Pleiadian contact experiences.\n\nThe documentary is also listed on the 'FIGU-Shop' website here:\nhttps://shop.figu.org/multimedia/filme/contact\n\nBilly himself (or his official organization) started a Youtube channel:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/c/figu/videos\nAnd a website:\nhttps://www.figu.org/\n...under the organization titled 'Freie Interessengemeinschaft\nUniversell' which translates to 'Free Community of Interests Universal', with a logo with the name 'Semjase-Silver-Star-Center'.\n\nThe Billy Meiers case is controversial, but also very well documented. I would be remiss not to include it. My summary here was formed after hearing opinions from the original investigators of the case. It needs to be pointed out that there is a surplus of further information and disinformation both (which can be difficult to distinguish) about this case available online. The beginning of Billy's story (as related in this documentary) was verified very strongly as you can see in the footage, *but* more stories on Billy Meier that came out after the documentary began to fade in authenticity. If this sort of piecewise-truthful saga (where it's hard to be certain what is legitimate) is not your cup of tea, feel free to ignore this case! It is included here for its significance as a point of reference on the recurring Pleiades connection. To that end, if your interest is in understanding the Pleiades connection, then digging into the research may be worth the effort. It is abundantly clear that this case became a mixed bag later on, with both proven truth to it, and proven falsehoods, although whether they can be attributed to Billy or his detractors is often unclear. It is uneducated, therefore, to say that this case is entirely honestly presented, or to say that it is \"all a hoax\". Such would be a limited, binary perspective demonstrating lack of research. In my opinion, the story is most useful in the present day as a grain of salt to better understand the Pleiades connection, which comes up time and again in contact scenarios to the present day. Paola Harris, Wendelle Stevens, the Elders, and others who have studied the case closely are certain that it began with a true story, which has all been verified through solid science as demonstrated in this documentary. It is considered possible that Billy became overly enamored with all of the attention he later received, and in later years may have began to make wilder claims for attention. It is thought he may have partially succumbed to the fan culture and become a sort of cult figure. It is even speculated he could even have been mentally affected by radiation from the crafts. This is a well-known side effect of many UFO encounters, that for instance Dr. Jacques Vall√©e and Dr. Hal Puthoff have discussed in talks (such as this one: https://youtu.be/-199qc_6090). This is all speculation. The verifiable story is that Billy began with a real experience and yet his story came to be found less believable /muddied, with the help of an endless supply of critics, and even his own wife. His wife Poppy, even though she helped record an anomalous sound once that even attracted nearby farmers in the area, was never fond of the attention (you can sense her frustration even in the documentary) and in later years divorced him and stated it was all a hoax. She was trying to get out of the public spotlight and get their kids out of the spotlight as well. Billy himself, and his daughter, at least, had suffered an attack from a harraser after attention was first brought to Billy's experience, and it understandably scared the family. Unfortunately, this sum decline shrouds the entire case in uncertainty to the average internet browser, but when you talk to the researchers who were there in the beginning, the earlier truth to the story becomes apparent. This is especially evident in this documentary. My suggestion: pay attention to the original findings, and take anything later on with a grain of salt. I encourage you to recognize the true facts and stick to those, without getting caught up in the controversial ones. Don't throw the baby (original research) out with the bathwater. He also found out that there was a lot of tampering going on behind the scenes by government figures, particularly with the hard evidence they had found.\nIt is also reminded that there are a huge number of eyewitnesses involved in the case. Again, this points to the importance of not considering it all a hoax, even if some of it in theory could be.\nLee describes how many items of evidence have been lost by people thinking it was better off in their hands, even before they met Billy he was losing stuff to people he shared it with.\nLee said he believed in Billy, and it became more realistic (from an Occam's Razor perspective) to believe Billy as time went on while he studied the case. Billy was a man with only one arm and the education of a sixth grader, and it became harder to believe that he was fooling the top scientists and computers in the United States with his evidence than to simply believe his story, especially given his warm personality. The case was hard to pin down, and amazing to the researchers, because every time they had one aspect, such as still photographs, analyzed, Billy would present them with another, such as sound recording tapes.\nLee recounts Billy mentioning the female extraterrestrial 'Menara' as being a Lyran, not a Pleiadian. Meier also described having contact with \"the Dals\".\nThey discuss (in part 5) the use of thought to control ships, and the sound of thoughts harmonizing.\nIt's pointed out that using models to do fake photography is very difficult or impossible for some of the evidence with regard to the foreground, shadows, and daylight. In fact, Spielberg spent a lot of money and then gave up trying to do a daylight UFO scene in Close Encounters of the Third Kind, but Billy has daylight footage. Billy also declined a large sum of money to \"explain how he does it\" and promptly replied something like \"Eh, it just happens.\" without much concern for the money and the thought of faking it all.\nIn part 7, they discuss a magnetic grid around the Earth which the ships ride or \"ground\" on, as a potential reason for the Schumann resonance being in audio recordings; the sound was all-encompassing for about a half mile; they also discuss the way the light is darkened around the ship before and after it appears in at least one piece of footage. John Bedini and Tom Bearden were researching this 3 20ths of a second long effect on the lighting. documentary can be watched on Youtube, from Billy's organization, here:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oNefLifaTVU\n\nNotable timestamps:\n‚Ä¢ Pleiades references are discussed especially at this timestamp:\nhttps://youtu.be/oNefLifaTVU?t=4248\nThis includes mention that \"The Great Pyramids of Egypt are also aligned to the Pleiades.\".\n‚Ä¢ discussion of the need to have a high vibration to make contact:\nhttps://youtu.be/oNefLifaTVU?t=2603\n\nNotes on information shared by Billy in the documentary:\n'Semjase' is the name by which Billy refers to the main female Pleiadian being he met. She was reportedly quite human in appearance. This is very similar to the description of the Pleiadian-connected Apunians whom Ricardo Gonz√°lez contacts, and serves to corroborate other Pleiadian contact experiences.\n\nThe documentary is also listed on the 'FIGU-Shop' website here:\nhttps://shop.figu.org/multimedia/filme/contact\n\nBilly himself (or his official organization) started a Youtube channel:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/c/figu/videos\nAnd a website:\nhttps://www.figu.org/\n...under the organization titled 'Freie Interessengemeinschaft\nUniversell' which translates to 'Free Community of Interests Universal', with a logo with the name 'Semjase-Silver-Star-Center'.\n\nThe Billy Meiers case is controversial, but also very well documented. I would be remiss not to include it. My summary here was formed after hearing opinions from the original investigators of the case. It needs to be pointed out that there is a surplus of further information and disinformation both (which can be difficult to distinguish) about this case available online. The beginning of Billy's story (as related in this documentary) was verified very strongly as you can see in the footage, *but* more stories on Billy Meier that came out after the documentary began to fade in authenticity. If this sort of piecewise-truthful saga (where it's hard to be certain what is legitimate) is not your cup of tea, feel free to ignore this case! It is included here for its significance as a point of reference on the recurring Pleiades connection. To that end, if your interest is in understanding the Pleiades connection, then digging into the research may be worth the effort. It is abundantly clear that this case became a mixed bag later on, with both proven truth to it, and proven falsehoods, although whether they can be attributed to Billy or his detractors is often unclear. It is uneducated, therefore, to say that this case is entirely honestly presented, or to say that it is \"all a hoax\". Such would be a limited, binary perspective demonstrating lack of research. In my opinion, the story is most useful in the present day as a grain of salt to better understand the Pleiades connection, which comes up time and again in contact scenarios to the present day. Paola Harris, Wendelle Stevens, the Elders, and others who have studied the case closely are certain that it began with a true story, which has all been verified through solid science as demonstrated in this documentary. It is considered possible that Billy became overly enamored with all of the attention he later received, and in later years may have began to make wilder claims for attention. It is thought he may have partially succumbed to the fan culture and become a sort of cult figure. It is even speculated he could even have been mentally affected by radiation from the crafts. This is a well-known side effect of many UFO encounters, that for instance Dr. Jacques Vall√©e and Dr. Hal Puthoff have discussed in talks (such as this one: https://youtu.be/-199qc_6090). This is all speculation. The verifiable story is that Billy began with a real experience and yet his story came to be found less believable /muddied, with the help of an endless supply of critics, and even his own wife. His wife Poppy, even though she helped record an anomalous sound once that even attracted nearby farmers in the area, was never fond of the attention (you can sense her frustration even in the documentary) and in later years divorced him and stated it was all a hoax. She was trying to get out of the public spotlight and get their kids out of the spotlight as well. Billy himself, and his daughter, at least, had suffered an attack from a harraser after attention was first brought to Billy's experience, and it understandably scared the family. Unfortunately, this sum decline shrouds the entire case in uncertainty to the average internet browser, but when you talk to the researchers who were there in the beginning, the earlier truth to the story becomes apparent. This is especially evident in this documentary. My suggestion: pay attention to the original findings, and take anything later on with a grain of salt. I encourage you to recognize the true facts and stick to those, without getting caught up in the controversial ones. Don't throw the baby (original research) out with the bathwater. Paola Harris writes that much here:\nhttps://www.ufocasebook.com/2009/harrisbelieves.html\nIn https://trello.com/c/BfNJQIyQ/1670-message-to-humanity-paola-harriss-interview-with-ricardo-gonz%C3%A1lez-in-argentina, Paola said:\n> I have been to Smidruti, Switzerland and I have seen Billy Meier, and I have studied the case with Wendelle Stevens, and it is real. Those were people and they were real, and the pictures are real because I talked to Wendelle Stevens,  who has passed away, who investigated the story and I went to see Billy Meier and I saw a lot when I was there.\nBilly's history and writing is still being studied, by Michael Horn for one, who has been studying it for over 40 years.\n\nLee Elders was interviewed to followup on the legacy of the case, sometime in 2011 or earlier, recorded here:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zJSHpO1jQpc&list=PL39ABA1509C3A9C86\nHe suggests that a lot of misinformation and enemies have come about since the original study; he and the original research team went in skeptical but found solid evidence; and as time went on the attention to evidence by others in the UFO research community was replaced by attempts at character assassination of Billy Meier. He also found out that there was a lot of tampering going on behind the scenes by government figures, particularly with the hard evidence they had found.\nIt is also reminded that there are a huge number of eyewitnesses involved in the case. Again, this points to the importance of not considering it all a hoax, even if some of it in theory could be.\nLee describes how many items of evidence have been lost by people thinking it was better off in their hands, even before they met Billy he was losing stuff to people he shared it with.\nLee said he believed in Billy, and it became more realistic (from an Occam's Razor perspective) to believe Billy as time went on while he studied the case. Billy was a man with only one arm and the education of a sixth grader, and it became harder to believe that he was fooling the top scientists and computers in the United States with his evidence than to simply believe his story, especially given his warm personality. The case was hard to pin down, and amazing to the researchers, because every time they had one aspect, such as still photographs, analyzed, Billy would present them with another, such as sound recording tapes.\nLee recounts Billy mentioning the female extraterrestrial 'Menara' as being a Lyran, not a Pleiadian. Meier also described having contact with \"the Dals\".\nThey discuss (in part 5) the use of thought to control ships, and the sound of thoughts harmonizing.\nIt's pointed out that using models to do fake photography is very difficult or impossible for some of the evidence with regard to the foreground, shadows, and daylight. In fact, Spielberg spent a lot of money and then gave up trying to do a daylight UFO scene in Close Encounters of the Third Kind, but Billy has daylight footage. Billy also declined a large sum of money to \"explain how he does it\" and promptly replied something like \"Eh, it just happens.\" without much concern for the money and the thought of faking it all.\nIn part 7, they discuss a magnetic grid around the Earth which the ships ride or \"ground\" on, as a potential reason for the Schumann resonance being in audio recordings; the sound was all-encompassing for about a half mile; they also discuss the way the light is darkened around the ship before and after it appears in at least one piece of footage. John Bedini and Tom Bearden were researching this 3 20ths of a second long effect on the lighting. The Beamship Trilogy footage is referenced.\nThey discuss that the Japanese did a program on the case for 30 million people to see, whereas United States media hardly covered it.\n\nAs an example of the number of eyewitnesses other than Meier, The Future of Mankind wiki purports lists of eyewitness testimonies:\nhttp://www.futureofmankind.co.uk/w/index.php?search=Witness+Testimony&title=Special%3ASearch&profile=default&fulltext=1\n\nHere Michael Horn discusses corroborations on aspects of Billy's story, even going into 2020:\nhttps://youtu.be/OKNgRhQU_5U\n\nThere was also a bit by the Swiss Radio and Television on his story:\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q9U3hLp_2BU\n\nHere is the full recording of the metal analysis in laboratory, which found that the metallic composition was very rare:\nhttps://youtu.be/Pwpoq4FiQyk\nIBM senior scientist Marcel Vogel: \"the samples were made by some kind of cold fusion process\"\n\nAs well, computer simulation analysis was done on the \"Wedding Cake UFO\" to prove it was 3.5 meters in diameter:\nhttp://rhalzahi.com/docs/WCUFO-EN-v2.pdf\n\nMichelle DellaFave, a singer/actress/dancer, was pictured in one of Billy's books with the label as being the Pleiadian extraterrestrial named 'Asket'. She met with Billy to discuss this with him, and find consensus in an understanding that it was a smear job against Billy (but also affecting Michelle's reputation), where photos Billy had captured were stolen and replaced in the photo lab under the threat of some troublemakers from the United States. Whether you want to believe this or not is entirely up to the viewer. The recommendation here is to listen to the heart of the speakers involved, and try out both perspectives, to decide the true cause behind the use of a photo of Michelle in Billy's books for yourself.\nhttps://youtu.be/YTlMuzdDXnA\nNotable timestamps from this video:\n‚Ä¢ Billy answers a question about possible other extraterrestrials being present on Earth that are instilling fear, and he responds that no, such don't exist, only benevolent Pleiadians are present, and they are just observing and providing some knowledge, particularly through Billy himself as a teacher to relay information:\nhttps://youtu.be/YTlMuzdDXnA?t=1908\nThe message that fear-instilling extraterrestrials are not present matches with everything else on this board, and is not surprising given the extensive concern in other cases over human nuclear activity, for instance.
